ited Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Selby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire) and Scottish: habitational name from Selby (Yorkshire). The placename may derive from Old English <i>sele</i> ‘willow copse’, sometimes alternating with <i>salh</i> ‘willow’, + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’.","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Shelby","meanings":["English (Essex and Middlesex): probably a variant of   Selby  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Selby was born about 1501, in Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, her father, William Selby, was 27 and her mother, Eleanor Hebborne De Gray, was 23. She married Thomas Rotherforth in 1520, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1535, in York, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 35."},"et":{"Abt 1501–1535":"umbes 1501–1535","1499–1555":"1499–1555","1501–1535":"1501–1535","1505–1542":"1505–1542","1508–Female":"1508–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1490–1523":"1490–1523","1523–1561":"1523–1561","1475–1565":"1475–1565","1479–1540":"1479–1540","1561":"1561","Abt 1501":"umbes 1501","1490":"1490","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","1479":"1479","1501":"1501","1555":"1555","1565":"1565","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1508":"1508","1505":"1505","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","England":"England","York, York district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire